# Experiment No. 4

# Title

Execute DML commands to manipulate data using SQL.

---

# Aim

To study and execute DML (Data Manipulation Language) commands to manipulate data in database tables using SQL.

---

# Theory

DML (Data Manipulation Language) commands are used to insert, update, delete, and retrieve data from database tables.

These commands work on the data stored inside the tables rather than changing the table structure.

DML commands are very important because they help users interact with the database and manage records efficiently.

Unlike DDL commands, DML commands do not automatically save changes permanently.
Changes can be controlled using:

* COMMIT
* ROLLBACK

---

# Types of DML Commands

| Command | Purpose                     |
| ------- | --------------------------- |
| INSERT  | Adds new records into table |
| UPDATE  | Modifies existing records   |
| DELETE  | Removes records from table  |
| SELECT  | Retrieves data from table   |

---

# 1. INSERT Command

## Theory

The INSERT command is used to add new records into a table.

---

## Syntax


INSERT INTO table_name
VALUES(value1, value2, value3);
```

---

## Example

```sql id="20fru9"
INSERT INTO Student
VALUES(1,'Ravi','Pune');
```

---

## Explanation

A new record is inserted into the Student table.

---

# 2. UPDATE Command

## Theory

The UPDATE command is used to modify existing records in a table.

The WHERE clause is generally used to specify which record should be updated.

---

## Syntax


UPDATE table_name
SET column_name = value
WHERE condition;
```

---

## Example


UPDATE Student
SET City='Mumbai'
WHERE RollNo=1;
```

---

## Explanation

The city of student whose RollNo is 1 changes from Pune to Mumbai.

---

# 3. DELETE Command

## Theory

The DELETE command removes records from a table.

The WHERE clause specifies which record should be deleted.

If WHERE clause is not used, all records are deleted.

---

## Syntax


DELETE FROM table_name
WHERE condition;
```

---

## Example


DELETE FROM Student
WHERE RollNo=1;
```

---

## Explanation

The record of student with RollNo 1 is deleted from the table.

---

# 4. SELECT Command

## Theory

The SELECT command retrieves data from database tables.

It is one of the most frequently used SQL commands.

---

## Syntax

SELECT column_name
FROM table_name;
```

---

## Example


SELECT * FROM Student;
```

---

## Explanation

All records and columns from Student table are displayed.

